photo.caption3: Bison in Lamar Valley
photo.alt_text4: Photo of black bear sow with cub

photo.alt_text1: A mountain reflecting in a lake.
photo.title1: Cathedral Peak and Lake in Autumn
photo.caption1: Cathedral Peak is one of the most recognizable peaks in the Yosemite Wilderness.
photo.alt_text2: A rainbow over a mountain in the distance.
photo.caption2: A hike up to Sentinel Dome rewards people with great views of the landscape around them.
photo.alt_text3: Mountains reflecting in water
photo.caption3: Glen Auilin is one of five High Sierra Camps, located in the Yosemite high country.
photo.alt_text4: Mountains surrounding a lake.
photo.caption4: Tenaya Lake is a favorite place to stop along the Tioga Road in summer.

photo.alt_text1: View of Logan Pass and the Continental Divide from the summit of Mt. Oberlin
photo.caption1: View of Logan Pass and the Continental Divide from the summit of Mt. Oberlin
photo.alt_text2: View of St. Mary Lake from Wild Goose Island Overlook
photo.title2: St. Mary Lake and Wild Goose Island
photo.caption2: View of St. Mary Lake from Wild Goose Island Overlook
photo.alt_text3: View of the mountains behind Lake McDonald at sunset
photo.caption3: Sunset on the mountains at the head of Lake McDonald
photo.alt_text4: Bowman Lake
photo.caption4: View of Bowman Lake in the northwest corner of the park

photo.alt_text1: The canyon glows orange as people visit Mather Point, a rock outcropping that juts into Grand Canyon
photo.title1: Grand Canyon Mather Point Sunset on the South Rim
photo.caption1: People come from all over the world to view Grand Canyon's sunset
photo.alt_text2: The Cape Royal viewpoint curves into the distance and closer rock formations jut into the canyon.
photo.title2: Grand Canyon National Park: View from Cape Royal on the North Rim
photo.caption2: A popular outdoor site for weddings and receptions, Cape Royal Amphitheater is located 23 miles (37 km) from the North Rim developed area.
photo.alt_text3: The Desert View Watchtower looms 70 feet into the air over a vast and dramatic view of the canyon.
photo.title3: Grand Canyon National Park: Desert View Watchtower (South Rim)
photo.caption3: The Watchtower is located at Desert View, the eastern-most developed area on the South Rim of Grand Canyon National Park.
photo.alt_text4: Tall canyon walls frame the wide Colorado river weaving back and forth.
photo.title4: Looking down the Colorado River from Nankoweap at river mile 53
photo.caption4: A view down the Colorado river from Nankoweap in Marble canyon.

photo.alt_text1: Backpackers in North Fork Cascade Canyon, Grand Teton behind
photo.caption1: Backpackers in North Fork Cascade Canyon approaching Paintbrush Divide.
photo.alt_text2: Winter sunrise on snow-covered Teton Range
photo.title2: Winter Sunrise on the Teton Range
photo.caption2: Winter sunrise on snow-covered Teton Range
photo.alt_text3: Grizzly bear running through dry grass with shrubs behind
photo.caption3: Grizzly bears are found throughout Grand Teton National Park
photo.alt_text4: Lake Solitude with the high Teton Peaks beyond during summer
photo.title4: Lake Solitude with the Cathedral Group
photo.caption4: Lake Solitude is a favorite hiking destination in the park.

photo.alt_text1: Zion Canyon Visitor Center
photo.caption1: The Zion Canyon Visitor Center sits under the watchful gaze of the Watchman
photo.alt_text2: Temples and Towers of the Virgin
photo.title2: Temples and Towers of the Virgin
photo.caption2: The Temples and Towers of the Virgin can be seen form the Human History Museum's back patio.
photo.alt_text3: Mountain of the Sun
photo.caption3: The Mountain of the Sun in Zion Canyon.
photo.alt_text4: The Zion Narrows
photo.caption4: The Zion Narrows is a challenging wilderness experience.

photo.alt_text1: a stone monolith reflected in standing water
photo.caption1: The Organ rock formation is reflected in one of many natural potholes.
photo.alt_text2: a broad, red arch with rock pinnacles in the background
photo.caption2: Double O Arch is one of many large arches in the Devils Garden area
photo.alt_text3: a stone arch
photo.caption3: Delicate Arch is perhaps the most famous natural arch in the world.
photo.alt_text4: the Milky Way arcs above silhouetted stone pinnacles
photo.title4: Milky Way over the Garden of Eden
photo.caption4: Arches offers some excellent night sky viewing.

photo.alt_text1: Longs Peak, covered in snow, against dark moody clouds.
photo.caption1: Longs Peak towers above Rocky Mountain National Park.
photo.alt_text2: Yellow flowers bloom on tundra slopes with mountains in the background.
photo.caption2: Old Man of the Mountain bloom on Rocky's alpine tundra.
photo.alt_text3: Road sweeps across open tundra with mountains in background.
photo.caption3: Trail Ridge Road, the highest continuous paved road in the United States, let's visitors experience Rocky's alpine tundra.
photo.alt_text4: A herd of elk stand in a meadow.
photo.caption4: In the fall, Rocky's elk gather together in groups for the mating season.

photo.alt_text1: A deep canyon with a forested floor and steep granite cliffs
photo.caption1: The Glaciers carved the Kings Canyon's steep granite cliffs, leaving a wide U-shaped valley.
photo.alt_text2: A steep granite slope leads from forest to a bare alpine landscape
photo.caption2: Just above Lodgepole Valley, the trail to the Watchtower offers views above the treeline.
photo.alt_text3: A guardrail encircles people along a narrow walkway with wide views
photo.caption3: A historic stairway leads to the top of Moro Rock, offering views from foothills to peaks
photo.alt_text4: A giant sequoia's reddish bark contrasts with the snow around it
photo.caption4: For those who don't mind icy roads, winter offers stunning views of sequoias in snow.

photo.alt_text1: hiker looks over Hidden Valley
photo.caption1: Scrambling to the top of boulders in Joshua Tree can get you a great view.
photo.alt_text2: a fiery sky behind the silhouette of a Joshua tree
photo.caption2: The wide-open desert of Joshua Tree National Park makes for stunning sunsets.
photo.alt_text3: an historic wood house seen through the missing windshield of an old, rusty vehicle
photo.caption3: The historic Keys Ranch can be visited only on a ranger-guided tour.
photo.alt_text4: night scene showing stars of the Milky Way over a sign saying "Entering Joshua Tree National Park"
photo.caption4: Enjoy some of the darkest night skies in Southern California.

photo.credit1: NPS Photo / Brian B. Roanhorse February 24, 2015
photo.alt_text1: Bryce Canyon Visitor Center Toll booths in winter.
photo.title1: Bryce Canyon Visitor Center Toll Booths
photo.caption1: Opening the gates at Bryce Canyon National Park under snow.
photo.credit2: NPS Photo / Brian B. Roanhorse February 28, 2015
photo.alt_text2: Snow on the Queens Garden Trail.
photo.caption2: Trail to Queens Garden is exceptional any day of the year.
photo.alt_text3: Orange Hoodoos under snow cover.
photo.caption3: Orange is the new look at Bryce.
photo.credit4: NPS Photo / Brian B. Roanhorse March 13, 2015
photo.alt_text4: Early morning snow at Thor' Hammer.
photo.caption4: Clear skys and snow drifts at Thor's Hammer.

photo.alt_text1: a rugged canyon
photo.caption1: The Maze is the most remote district of the park. Visiting requires four-wheel drive, self-reliance, and extra time.
photo.alt_text2: a broad stone arch with rock pinnacles in the distance
photo.caption2: Mesa Arch, at Island in the Sky, is a great spot for photographers.
photo.alt_text3: shallow pools with a double rainbow in the background
photo.caption3: Pothole Point Trail
photo.alt_text4: a long gravel road with cyclists on it
photo.caption4: The White Rim Road at Island in the Sky is a popular road for mountain bikers.

photo.alt_text1: Sunset paints the glaciers of Mount Rainier in pink and gold.
photo.caption1: Every scenic overlook shows a different side of Mount Rainier. Viewed from Gobblers Knob Lookout at sunset, the glaciers covering the mountain turn pink and gold.
photo.alt_text2: Purple lupine and white bistort bloom in a meadow alongside a sign for the Wonderland Trail.
photo.title2: Wildflower Meadow Along the Wonderland Trail
photo.caption2: Both the Wonderland Trail and subalpine meadows encircle Mount Rainier. Summertime blooms splatter the hillsides with color.
photo.alt_text3: Towering cedars and douglas-firs reach skyward while a beam of sun breaks through the canopy.
photo.caption3: With some of the few remaining old-growth forests in the Cascade Mountains, Mount Rainier National Park protects native plants great and small in places like the Grove of the Patriarchs.
photo.alt_text4: A hoary marmot with white frosted fur rests on a rock beside white flowers in a meadow.
photo.caption4: From small amphibians and hoary marmots to the black bears and elk, many animals call the wild places of Mount Rainier home.

photo.alt_text1: A thick layer of frost covers the fields, trees, and mountains in Cades Cove.
photo.caption1: Wintertime brings a quiet beauty to the Great Smoky Mountains.
photo.alt_text2: Wisps of fog hang over the forests in the mountains.
photo.caption2: The park gets its name from mists that often rise like smoke from the mountains.
photo.alt_text3: Tombstones stand in front of a white, wooden church on a foggy morning.
photo.title3: A Foggy Morning at Cades Cove Methodist Church
photo.caption3: Historic buildings such as churches, gristmills, barns, and homes allow visitors to get a feel for life in the mountains before the national park was created.
photo.alt_text4: Rhododendron bushes line the banks of a stream filled with large boulders.
photo.title4: The Waters of Roaring Fork Below Grotto Falls
photo.caption4: Abundant rainfall means lush forests and beautiful stream scenes in the Great Smoky Mountains.

photo.alt_text1: A man stands on a rocky outcrop overlooking the receding mountains.
photo.caption1: There are over 60 peaks with an elevation over 3,000 feet in Shenandoah.
photo.alt_text2: A man stands with his back facing us, looking at a waterfall.
photo.caption2: Dark Hollow Falls, at 70 feet, is our most visited waterfall.
photo.alt_text3: A close up shot of a Red-Bellied Woodpecker with a blurry teal background.
photo.caption3: There are over 200 species of bird that call Shenandoah "home."
photo.alt_text4: A road surrounded by fall foliage turns a curve around a small waterfall.
photo.caption4: There are 105 miles to explore on Skyline Drive.

photo.alt_text1: Large puffy clouds dot a brilliant blue sky as wave crash against the rocky coastline of Acadia.
photo.caption1: Millions of people come to Acadia for our distinctive rocky coastline.
photo.alt_text2: A brilliant sunset filled with hues of blue, red, orange, magenta, and purple highlight the sky.
photo.caption2: As the tallest point on the eastern seaboard Cadillac Mountain provides fantastic viewpoints.
photo.alt_text3: Two hikers ascend a sheer cliff trail by way of historic iron rung ladders.
photo.caption3: Whether it's a stroll along Ocean Path or a difficult ascent up The Precipice, there are hiking trails for everyone!
photo.alt_text4: A man peers into a telescope as the Milky Way lights up the night sky.
photo.caption4: With dark skies, Acadia is a fantastic place to come see the stars.

photo.alt_text1: A ranger explains the cave to visitors in the vast expanse of the passage called Broadway.
photo.caption1: A ranger explains Mammoth Cave in the vast passage known as Broadway. Rotunda, one of the cave's largest rooms, is just ahead.
photo.alt_text2: Dripstone formations create a panoply of textures in the Frozen Niagara section of Mammoth Cave
photo.caption2: Dripstone formations create a panoply of textures in the Frozen Niagara section of Mammoth Cave as slowly dripping water redeposits dissolved limestone over the course of centuries. Image is a panoramic composite.
photo.alt_text3: A girl peers wonderingly into the shadows of Mammoth Cave.
photo.caption3: Mammoth Cave's shadows have beckoned the explorer deep within its visitors for geneerations, asking the question "Where does that lead? What lies in the dark places?" The questions remain as compelling today as they did for the first explorers.
photo.alt_text4: A kayaker paddles up the languid waters of the Green River in Mammoth Cave National Park.
photo.title4: Green River in Mammoth Cave National Park
photo.caption4: More than 30 miles of the Green and Nolin Rivers course through Mammoth Cave NP, representing one of the most biologically diverse river systems in the Eastern United States. Their languid waters are a magnet for canoeist, kayakers and anglers.

photo.alt_text1: Two canoes at Nine Mile Pond during sunset.
photo.caption1: A meeting ground of marsh and mangrove environments. You may see alligators, wading birds, turtles, and fish.
photo.alt_text2: An American Alligator high walks the Anhinga Trail.
photo.caption2: An American Alligator high walks the Anhinga Trail.
photo.alt_text3: Two visitors bike along the road in Shark Valley.
photo.title3: Shark Valley Tram and Bicycle Road
photo.caption3: Biking is a great way to experience the quiet beauty of the Everglades.
photo.alt_text4: An aerial view of the landscape transition from Sawgrass to Florida Bay.
photo.title4: Transition from Sawgrass to Florida Bay
photo.caption4: An aerial view of the landscape transition from Sawgrass to Florida Bay.

photo.alt_text1: Park visitors enjoy a sunset on the moat wall.
photo.caption1: Sunsets at the Dry Tortugas are breathtaking. Visitors who choose to camp over night can view the sun set at Fort Jefferson.
photo.alt_text2: A view of Fort Jefferson from the moat all.
photo.caption2: ort Jefferson is a massive but unfinished coastal fortress. It is the largest masonry structure in the Americas, and is composed of over 16 million bricks.
photo.alt_text3: A boat passes in front of Loggerhead Key during sunset.
photo.caption3: The largest island in the Dry Tortugas, Loggerhead Key is a site of shipwrecks, a significant lighthouse installation, and where the historic Carnegie Laboratory for Marine Ecology once stood. Named for its abundance of loggerhead sea turtles, Loggerhead
photo.alt_text4: A view inside Fort Jefferson.
photo.caption4: Garden Key is the second largest island in the Dry Tortugas, about 14 acres in size, and has had the most human impact. Located on Garden Key is historic Fort Jefferson, one of the nation’s largest 19th century forts and a central cultural feature of Dry

photo.alt_text1: Glow from Halema‘uma‘u Crater
photo.caption1: Halema‘uma‘u glows in the pre-dawn darkness
photo.alt_text2: Couple hiking Halema‘uma‘u Trail
photo.caption2: A couple hikes the Halema‘uma‘u Trail through rain forest from the summit of Kilauea to the caldera fllor.
photo.alt_text3: Visitors in a lava tube
photo.caption3: Nāhuku, also known as Thurston Lava Tube is a very popular stop. Come early to beat the crowds.
photo.alt_text4: Steam from the Steaming Bluff
photo.caption4: The Steaming Bluff is near the Steam Vents area. Rain water seeps down to hot earth and returns as steam.

photo.alt_text1: A wooden bridge crosses Redwood Creek in the redwood forest
photo.caption1: Summer is a busy time at Muir Woods. Visit early in the morning for the most pleasant experience.
photo.alt_text2: Black fire scars are visible on trunks of large redwood trees
photo.caption2: Many fires over the centuries have encouraged new growth and opened up the under story of the redwood forest. Black scars are present among the oldest of redwoods in Muir Woods.
photo.alt_text3: Sun rays shine down on a visitor among very tall redwood trees
photo.caption3: Later afternoon is a gorgeous time of day to visit Bohemian Grove, inside Muir Woods.
photo.alt_text4: A Lady Fern grows over Redwood Creek
photo.caption4: At least ten species of ferns grow in Muir Woods - fern seem to grow larger in redwood forests than other forests - possibly competing for attention from the redwoods?
